align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: play with percentages</span><hr size=1> Yes, it was meant to be read as so far over the edge of reasonability as to be funny.<br>
<br>
Our current tax system is supposed to tax people's disposable income.  The more you make, the more is disposable, the more you get taxed.  Thats why there are personal, Head of Household, and dependent deductions.<br>
A person making $25000/year living in his parents house (rent free or reduced) has a LOT more disposable income than a family of 4 making the same, and living independently.  And our current system recognizes that.  Taking money from the single guy is unlikely to result in him not being able to meet basic needs (food, clothing, shelter, transportation) but taking the same amount from the family might.<br>
Now... as to the fact that the current system, in addition to deductions, has a graduation such that higher adjusted incomes (after personal/HoH/Dependent deductions) pay a greater percentage than lower ones, one has to consider the concept of diminishing utility.  Basically, Diminishing utility is the idea that as you get more and more of something, each addition provides less use than the one before.  For example..Its great to have a hammer around the house.  A second hammer isnt as useful, but hey, a spare is OK.  A third hammer has even less use.  By the time youre up to the 109th hammer... what the heck use is it?  So little as to ammount to none.  But that very same hammer would be quite useful to a guy who doenst have one at all.  The theory is that money also has a diminishing utility.  The more you have, the less you'll really miss it if its taken in taxes.  A lot of people disagree with this of course.<br>
Finally, our current system is also used by the Govt as a means of encouraging and discouraging certain activities.  This is where you get other deductions.  Charity is tax deductible.  Interest on a home loan is deductible.  A plethora of other things become deductible if you have enough money or time to delve into the tax code, like the rich do.<br>
<br>
